      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThis enormous gap is primarily a **denticity effect**: EDTA is a hexadentate ligand (4 carboxylates + 2 amines), while NTA is tetradentate (3 carboxylates + 1 amine). EDTA wraps around Fe³⁺ more completely, satisfying its octahedral coordination sphere and releasing more water molecules (greater entropic gain, ΔS = 442.7 J/mol·K for EDTA vs 349.8 for NTA). The thermodynamic data also reveals that Fe³⁺–EDTA formation is **exothermic** (ΔH = −11.3 kJ/mol), while Fe³⁺–NTA is **endothermic** (ΔH = +13.4 kJ/mol) — meaning EDTA wins on both enthalpic and entropic grounds. This is why EDTA is the preferred chelating agent in iron-sequestration applications (e.g., micronutrient fertilizers, analytical masking agents).\n\n*Source: NIST SRD-46 (vlm_108639 for EDTA; vlm_105553 for NTA)*",
